			<div class="blogComment">
				<a name="109262624144301760"></a> 
				Sony is suffering from their same delusions of usefulness they've had for years.  I predict that their product will die as all Sony self-indulgences die, a quick burst of sales and then nothing.  At least it should, but Sony's gotten lucky in the past thanks to spoiled children and larger children that can't manage their college fund.  After that, they'll grudgingly jump on Microsoft's Personal Media Player train just in time to suck up all the overhead and drown in competition because they were late to market.  Then they'll suck up to Microsoft and get on launch for Personal Media Player 2.0, which will be a lesser evolution than Apple's We Invented Everything 2.0, and barely break even thanks to Microsoft having their OEMs by the balls.<br /><br />My vote for best lossy audio format goes to Ogg Vorbis, lossless audio goes to FLAC.  I won't go into that now, though.  The main thing to remember about converting from MP3 to ATRAC, apart from the fact that you're throwing away compatibility, is that they're both lossy formats.  MP3 strips away data during it's compression, and then ATRAC  takes away a little more as its algorithym determines different information to be extraneous between frames.  Converting from lossy to anything is just silly, particulary to yet more lossy.  Better to just start over with your new lossy format or go to lossless (lossy versus lossless is a LONG discussion).<br />
